I came across this while looking for a good, accepted translation of
タオルケット and thought it might be useful for others:

http://nihongodecarenavi.jp/index.html

&quot;Nihongo de Care-navi is a Japanese-English / English-Japanese
dictionary with useful expressions in nursing and caretaking scenes for
supporting your Japanese Language learning.&quot;

As the site's stated mission implies, it does contain a lot of really
basic stuff, but there's some good jargon in there as well.  It doesn't
look like you'll be treated to the kanji unless you're using the
Japanese interface; you can switch between interfaces at any time by
clicking the language button at the top right.

&lt;aside&gt;Speaking of kanji, I was just reading a kind of manga-blog by
someone working in Japan &quot;as [the] translator in a software company&quot;,
drawing several sketches of himself apparently translating computer
terms at a keyboard.  Later, he noted that someone who could read kanji
could do a whole lot with the buttons on a washlet panel, but as someone
who did not read kanji, he was totally in the dark.  Yadda yadda yadda,
hilarity ensues.
What really flabbergasted me was that someone supposedly working as a
translator--in Japan, no less, and in-house--could actually not read
kanji.  Is this even possible?
I guess this is a rhetorical question, but if anyone feels like
answering, he or she should probably make a new thread for it.&lt;/aside&gt;

Nora

