At the risk of dating myself here, I cut my translation teeth working
in-house at an agency that had been founded in the 1950s by a GI who married
a Japanese woman and decided to stay in Japan. In his decades in Japan he
never learned to read kanji, but his understanding of the language was good.
He had some very sharp marketing people (Japanese), a handful of in-house
translators (mostly Mormons who decided to stay in Japan beyond their
missionary terms), and a crew of six or eight Japanese &quot;OLs&quot; who transcribed
every text into romaji as a prep step for translation. Crude but effective.
This was before word processors of any kind. For me, this was a tremendous
learning-aid, as I was actively memorizing kanji. Last I knew (within the
past couple of years), that agency was still in business.

Terry Gallagher
Eastham, MA USA
