Wow. That is just bizarre. I just assumed that one of the requirements of being a translator was the capability to not only read newspapers, magazines, novels, textbooks, and such other everyday text with little or no aide from a dictionary but also the ability to accurately and naturally convey it in your native language. If they are symbols you have never seen that represent words that you've never heard, how could you presume to translate anything accurately? This &quot;thread&quot; (don't know what else to call it) has really opened my eyes to this chilling reality that there are people like that out there.

I've always wondered why Japanese people who I've already told my profession to ask me &quot;So, can you read Japanese?&quot; In general, my usual response is something like, &quot;If I couldn't, I wouldn't be able to do my job...&quot; or &quot;Didn't I just tell you what I do for a living?&quot; Me saying that I was a translator should have included the meaning that I can speak, understand, read, and write Japanese. Perhaps this kanji-illiterate translator thing is actually not so rare...

