Here, I'd rather say an understanding of the structure of words is
necessary rather than a thorough knowledge of kanji. Words (homonyms)
don't come without context and even without the _image_ of the sound
that is the kanji, it is easy to say &quot;hankou&quot; with &quot;han&quot; as in
&quot;hantai&quot; ?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I studied Latin
&gt; in high school (yes, I'm one of those strange ones!), and it
&gt; definitely
&gt; helped me with my understanding of my own language. It certainly
&gt; helped me
&gt; out on the SAT and GRE! Using an exam metaphor, kanji is to
&gt; Japanese as
&gt; Latin is to English! They are the building blocks of the language.
">

I'd say that especially in Japanese, it is the hearing that supports
the reading more than the opposite _because_ it is possible to get a
word's meaning _without_ being able to sound out the kanjis.

In alphabet based languages, once the (limited) written system is
understood it is possible to connect the reading to the sound the
word actually makes, which I think is what helps the learning
process. It is not just &quot;reading&quot; that is involved but actually
sounding out the word (even if in one's mind), and even if the
pronunciation is mistaken, it is _systematically_ mistaken so when
the system is corrected it is easier to leverage the memorized sounds
into actual speech.

Jean-Christophe
